These are questionable assumptions, to put it charitably, but they are beside the point.Â  Aslan is hoping to discredit and classify into irrelevance those who publicly insist, as I have (and he quotes me), that religion is âinnately backward, obscurantist, irrational and dangerous.âÂ  Backward, because it relies not on reason for solutions, but on looking to ancient texts for ready-made answers.Â  Obscurantist, because it discourages searching for truthes about our world using empirical methods.Â  Irrational, because (for starters) the very notion that this or that shepherd or merchant ages ago was chosen by a divine being to deliver a message valid eternally and for all humanity offends reason and commonsense.Â  Dangerous, because (again, just for starters), armed with âholyâ texts, the faithful practice all sorts of mischief and savagery, damaging both members of their own communities and those outside them. Â But atheist or antitheist, no matter: what counts is the shared bedrock of nonbelief, the refusal to accept as fact, and defer to, what is asserted without evidence.
There can be only one reason that Aslan adduces his taxonomy of nonbelievers: to confuse the argument, this time by claiming that atheists (or antitheists) are busy propagating a fundamentalism of their own, and a potentially murderous one at that.Â  Once harmless, some of the faithless, in his telling, have been horribly transmogrified into wannabe tyrants.Â  He opens a brief but otherwise interesting historical excursus on the roots of nonbelief by erroneously deciphering the Greek roots of the word atheist, atheos, which breaks down not as âwithout godsâ but âwithout god.âÂ  In any case, antitheists, from the middle of the 19th century, he says, have professed a âstridently militant form of atheism,â and seen Â âreligion as an insidious force that must be rooted from society â forcibly if necessary.â
