No matter how many times Aslan deploys such sophistry, it will not work.Â  Nonbelievers reject the comic-book cosmogony propounded as âsacred truthâ by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam â âsacred truthâ far too many in the present day are eager to die, mutilate, and kill for.Â  We ask, quite rightly, how reasonable people could believe it.Â  We dismiss as incompatible with modern life the master-slave ethos, the affirmation of slavery as an institution, the patriarchal misogyny, the wanton punitive cruelty (check out Leviticus, for example), the vile stigmatization of gays, and the shaming of the female body that permeate the religious dogma and its canon.
We understand the real purpose behind religion whenever it exceeds the bounds of conscience, as it has done throughout history, and seeps into politics.Â  More than two centuries ago, the English and American revolutionary Thomas Paine penned words that still ring true: âAll national institutions of churches, whether Jewish, Christian or Turkish, appear to me no other than human inventions, set up to terrify and enslave mankind, and monopolize power and profit.â
Atheists, New and old, hold religion to be of human provenance and based on texts of human authorship riddled with human flaws exploitable for entirely profane purposes.Â  Once one ceases regarding religion as quaint myth or a source of comfort (albeit false) for those who accept it, and begins grasping the lethal force it is regaining in much of the world, alarm and outrage ensue.
